(44, 1, '2017-09-26 09:30:59', '2017-09-26 09:30:59', '<div data-ce-tag=\"spacer\"></div>\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Attribute Filters</span>  </h1>\r\n\r\nDRIVER syncs with the database designer schema to make filterable fields available to users. Fields marked as filterable/searchable are included in the filter bar.\r\n\r\nThere are two ways to filter incidents on the DRIVER website: through the List View, or the Map View. Attribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for the List View option of the DRIVER website.\r\n\r\nThe Attribute Filters can be found on the topmost bar of the DRIVER website upon accessing the Map.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Attribute Filters and How to Access Them</span>  </h3>\r\n\r\n[IMG: The top bar with labels of the types of Attribute Filters]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Text Search</span>\r\n\r\nSearching in the text box will narrow down the incidents to ones that include the search term in a field marked as filterable/searchable in the database designer. Typing multiple words will perform a search for incidents that have both of the words in one or more fields.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Date Filter [WORD BETTER]</span>\r\n\r\nThe date filter has a clickable interface to choose minimum and maximum dates for display and analysis. The default range is the previous ninety days.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Option Filter</span>\r\n\r\nEnumeration fields (select lists, checkboxes) are included as attribute filter dropdown buttons. Selecting an option applies that filter to the data. Multiple options may be selected for any filter. Active filters are highlighted in light blue in the interface.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Numeric Filter</span>\r\n\r\nFields containing numbers may be filtered using a minimum/maximum range in the numeric filter.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>\r\n\r\n• List View\r\n\r\n• Spatial Filters\r\n\r\n• Saving Filters\r\n\r\n• Clearing Filters\r\n\r\n', 'Attribute Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '40-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-26 09:30:59', '2017-09-26 09:30:59', '', 40, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/40-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(45, 1, '2017-09-26 09:31:34', '2017-09-26 09:31:34', '[:en]Applied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks.\r\n\r\nSaved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\" xlink=\"href\">spatial filters.</a>\r\n<h3>Saving Filters</h3>\r\nAny chosen set of filters can be saved for later use.\r\n\r\nTo save a filter, simply click the “Saved Filters” button on the top right corner of the screen.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-375 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Highlight_Filters_Layers_03.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"199\" />\r\n\r\nA pop-up should appear that shows the user’s saved filters (if any). Below, you’ll find a box that says “Add New Saved Filter.”\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-436 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Saved_Filters_Filter-Name.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1365\" height=\"639\" />\r\n\r\nEnter your desired Filter name, and click on “Save Filter.” The new saved filter should now appear inside the pop up.\r\n<h3>Clearing Filters</h3>\r\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button on the top right corner of the screen, next to the Saved Filters button. This can be done for both the Map Interface and the Record List.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-437 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/02_Record-List_09-Filtering_Clearing-Filters.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"800\" height=\"443\" />\r\n<h3>Related Articles</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\" xlink=\"href\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\" xlink=\"href\">Spatial Filters</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\" xlink=\"href\">Attribute Filters</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces/\" xlink=\"href\">View Interfaces</a></li>\r\n</ul>[:Ph]\r\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks.\r\n\r\nSaved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\">spatial filters.</a>\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Saving Filters</span>  </h1>\r\n\r\nAny chosen set of filters can be saved for later use.\r\n\r\nTo save a filter, simply click the “Saved Filters” button on the top right corner of the screen.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">REQUESTED</span>\r\n\r\nA pop-up should appear that shows the user’s saved filters (if any). Below, you’ll find a box that says “Add New Saved Filter.”\r\n\r\n<b><u>MINE</u></b>\r\n\r\nEnter your desired Filter name, and click on “Save Filter.” The new saved filter should now appear inside the pop up.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">REQUESTED</span>\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Clearing Filters</span>  </h1>\r\n\r\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button on the top right corner of the screen, next to the Saved Filters button.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces/\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', 'Saving & Clearing Filters', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'saving-and-clearing-filters', '', '', '2017-10-02 18:44:51', '2017-10-02 18:44:51', '', 0, 'http://roadsafety.ph/?page_id=45', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(46, 1, '2017-09-26 09:31:34', '2017-09-26 09:31:34', 'Saving & Clearing Filters\r\n\r\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks. Saved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and spatial filters.\r\n\r\nHow to Save Filters\r\nThis is how you save filters.\r\n\r\nHow to Clear Filters\r\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button.\r\n\r\n\r\nRelated Articles\r\n•	Map View vs List View\r\n•	Spatial Filters\r\n•	Attribute Filters\r\n', 'Saving & Clearing Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-26 09:31:34', '2017-09-26 09:31:34', '', 45, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
