(164, 1, '2017-09-27 12:33:17', '2017-09-27 12:33:17', '<div data-ce-tag=\"spacer\"></div>\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Filtering &amp; Searching</span>  </h1>\n\nDRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.\n\nWhile there are two View Interface types on the DRIVER website (<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a> &amp; <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map Interface</a>), there are also two types of filtering &amp; searching features available:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters.</a>&nbsp;. Attribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website, while Spatial Filters are primarily used for the Map Interface.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as a geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – Attribute Filters and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the Map Interface.\n\n', 'Filtering & Searching', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-27 12:33:17', '2017-09-27 12:33:17', '', 89, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(165, 1, '2017-09-27 12:34:14', '2017-09-27 12:34:14', '<div data-ce-tag=\"spacer\"></div>\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Filtering &amp; Searching</span>  </h1>\n\nDRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.\n\nWhile there are two View Interface types on the DRIVER website (<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a> &amp; <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map Interface</a>), there are also two types of filtering &amp; searching features available:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters.</a>&nbsp;. Attribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website, while Spatial Filters are primarily used for the Map Interface.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as a geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – Attribute Filters and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the Map Interface.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks. Saved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and spatial filters.\n\n', 'Filtering & Searching', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-27 12:34:14', '2017-09-27 12:34:14', '', 89, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(166, 1, '2017-09-27 12:35:24', '2017-09-27 12:35:24', '<div data-ce-tag=\"spacer\"></div>\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Filtering &amp; Searching</span>  </h1>\n\nDRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.\n\nWhile there are two <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces\">View Interfaces</a> on the DRIVER website (<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a> &amp; <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map Interface</a>), there are also two types of filtering &amp; searching features available:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters.</a>&nbsp;. Attribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website, while Spatial Filters are primarily used for the Map Interface.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as a geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – Attribute Filters and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the Map Interface.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks. Saved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and spatial filters.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  View Interfaces  </li>  <li>  Attribute Filters  </li>  <li>  Spatial Filters  </li>  <li>  Saving &amp; Clearing Filters  </li>  </ul>', 'Filtering & Searching', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-27 12:35:24', '2017-09-27 12:35:24', '', 89, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(169, 1, '2017-09-28 05:11:06', '2017-09-28 05:11:06', '\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks.\n\nSaved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and spatial filters.\n\n<h1> <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Saving Filters</span> </h1>\n\nAny chosen set of filters can be saved for later use.\n\nTo save a filter, simply click the \"Saved Filters\" button on the top right corner of the screen.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\nA pop-up should appear that shows the user\'s saved filters (if any). Below, you\'ll find a box that says \"Add New Saved Filter.\"\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nEnter your desired Filter name, and click on \"Save Filter.\" The new saved filter should now appear inside the pop up.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\n<h1> <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Clearing Filters</span> </h1>\n\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button on the top right corner of the screen, next to the Saved Filters button.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3> <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span> </h3> <p style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Map View vs List View<br> • Spatial Filters<br> • Attribute Filters</p>', 'Saving & Clearing Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-autosave-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 10:01:42', '2017-09-28 10:01:42', '', 45, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/45-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(171, 1, '2017-09-28 05:32:50', '2017-09-28 05:32:50', '\n\nThere are three ways that a user can view and access data on the DRIVER website: Through the dashboard, the record list view, or the map view. All incidents recorded in DRIVER can be accessed through the record list view and the map view; the dashboard is the default view after the user logs in, and provides a summary of incidents of DRIVER’s data within a specific period of time.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\">Dashboard</a></span>  </h3>\n\nThe dashboard interface is the default view after logging in, and includes application defaults that allow the user to access an overview of information about the data in DRIVER.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a></span>  </h3>\n\nThe record list is simply a collection of all incidents recorded on the DRIVER website, shown in tabular form. Incidents in this view may be filtered using <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, which help the user narrow down their searches to dates, reporting agency, and severity, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAside from a visual representation of where the incidents occurred, the map interface also provides the user with filters called <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a>, that allow for drawing geographic boundaries on the map using special drawing tools.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\">Dashboard</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'View Interfaces', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '107-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 05:32:50', '2017-09-28 05:32:50', '', 107, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/107-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(172, 1, '2017-09-28 05:37:36', '2017-09-28 05:37:36', '[:en]<a href=\"http://roadsafety.gov.ph\">DRIVER</a> is web application designed to view, collect, and analyze road incident data in the Philippines, particularly traffic incidents, disruptions, and crimes. The application provides data viewing and entry tools such as graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.\r\n<h3>User Types &amp; Roles</h3>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\">There are three different types of users on the DRIVER website, each with a designated role.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\"><strong>Public Viewers</strong> may view data on DRIVER, but with limitations (i.e. they may not access vehicle plate numbers and names of persons involved incidents, etc).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\"><strong>Analysts</strong> may enter, edit, and export data.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\"><strong>Administrators </strong>have login capabilities to the database and design editor of the software, and can modify the structure of the DRIVER database.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><em><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-and-roles/\">More information on User Types &amp; Roles</a></em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Accessing DRIVER</h3>\r\nThe DRIVER website can be accessed by going to <a href=\"http://roadsafety.gov.ph.\">http://roadsafety.gov.ph.</a> If a user has an account with a supported provider (e.g. Google), they may enter the DRIVER website by clicking on the “Log in with Google’” button, and selecting or inputting their login details.\r\n\r\nIf needed, admin users may also grant login access to other user types by providing other users with their own login details.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;[:Ph]\r\nDRIVER is designed to view, collect, and analyze road incident data in the Philippines, particularly traffic incidents, disruptions, and crimes. The application provides data viewing and entry tools, graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-and-roles\" xlink=\"href\">User Types &amp; Roles</a>  </h3>  <p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\">There are different <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-roles\" xlink=\"href\">types of users</a> on the DRIVER website, each with a designated role. <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/public-viewer\" xlink=\"href\">Public Viewers</a> may view data on DRIVER, but with limitations (i.e. they may not access plate numbers, names of persons involved incidents, etc).</p>  <p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/analyst\" xlink=\"href\">Analysts</a>&nbsp;may enter, edit, and export data.</p>  <p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/administrator\" xlink=\"href\">Administrators</a>&nbsp;have login capabilities to the database and design editor of the software, and can modify the structure of the database.</p>  <h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/accessing-driver\" xlink=\"href\">Accessing DRIVER</a>  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe DRIVER website can be accessed through&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.gov.ph.\" xlink=\"href\">http://roadsafety.gov.ph.</a>&nbsp;If a user has an account with a supported provider (e.g. Google), they may enter the domain by clicking on the “Log in with Google’” button, and select their user.\r\n\r\nIf needed, admin users may also grant login access to other user types by providing other users with their own login details.\r\n\r\n<h3>  Related Articles  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/accessing-driver\" xlink=\"href\">Accessing Driver</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://user-types-and-permissions\" xlink=\"href\">User Types &amp; Permissions</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-tools\" xlink=\"href\">Important Tools on DRIVER</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\" xlink=\"href\">Explore the Dashboard</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', '[:en]About DRIVER[:tl]Getting Started[:Ph]Tungkol sa DRIVER[:]', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'about-driver', '', '', '2017-12-08 08:38:18', '2017-12-08 08:38:18', '', 0, 'http://roadsafety.ph/?p=172', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(173, 1, '2017-09-28 05:37:36', '2017-09-28 05:37:36', '', 'Getting Started', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '172-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 05:37:36', '2017-09-28 05:37:36', '', 172, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/172-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(174, 1, '2017-09-28 05:38:16', '2017-09-28 05:38:16', '<div data-ce-tag=\"spacer\"></div>\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Signing In</span>  </h1>\n\nIf a user has an account with a supported provider (e.g. Google), they can click on the “Log in with provider’” button. This process redirects to the provider’s authentication page, and after a successful login, redirects back to DRIVER with the user’s credentials\n\nAdministrators may also create username and password pairs for users to log in.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">How to Sign In</span>  </h3>\n\nYou’ll need a Google Account before you can sign in to DRIVER. If you already have one, simply click on the “Log in With Google Account” button to proceed to the website.\n\nCertain administrators of DRIVER may also create and assign username and password combinations for others. For users who have their own non-Google login details provided by DRIVER administrators, you may simply enter your username and password, click the “Sign In” button, and proceed to the website.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:normal;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-roles\">User Types &amp; Roles</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/getting-started/\">Getting Started</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Signing In', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '99-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 05:38:16', '2017-09-28 05:38:16', '', 99, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/99-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(175, 1, '2017-09-28 05:42:52', '2017-09-28 05:42:52', '\n\nThere are three roles with differing permissions in DRIVER: the (1) Admin, (2) Analyst, and (3) Public Viewer. Each \"user type\" or role provides different levels of functionality, and some have limited access to certain parts of DRIVER.&nbsp;\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Admin</span>  </h3>\n\nThe admin role has access to the most functionality in the application, including login capability to the database design editor software. Admins can modify the structure of the database, add new fields, make fields required, upload geographic boundaries, and manage users. The database design editor software will be covered in a separate user manual. In DRIVER, admins may export user access logs for analysis.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Analyst</span>  </h3>\n\nThe analyst role includes permissions to view and edit all data in DRIVER. Analysts may add, edit, and delete incidents and interventions, and have access to all event information, including details associated with an incident such as people and vehicle information.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Public Viewer</span>  </h3>\n\nPublic users may register to view basic incident data. They may not edit any data, and can not view person or vehicle information.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/getting-started/\">Getting Started</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\">Dashboard</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record Lists</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'User Types & Roles', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '95-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 05:42:52', '2017-09-28 05:42:52', '', 95, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/95-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
