(206, 1, '2017-09-28 07:42:12', '2017-09-28 07:42:12', '\n\nThe map interface is one of the principal tools in the DRIVER application, and is used to view incidents in a variety of ways, such as through filter tools, layers, and more. Depending on the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types\">type of user</a>, the Map also grants access to interventions, additional graphs, custom report builder tools, and data exports, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">How to Access the Map</span>  </h3>\n\nWhile there are small map sections available on the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\">Dashboard</a>, the main Map interface can be accessed by clicking on the the “Dashboard” drop down on the topmost left bar on the DRIVER dashboard.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Important Map Tools</span>  </h3>  <h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/layers/\">Layers</a>  </h3>\n\nLayers allow users to further narrow down the map interface according to Street or Satellite View, or through setting the layer to only show Incidents, Interventions, Heatmap, Blackspots, City/Province, or Region. By setting a layer, users will be able to choose what kind of incident data they want to access.\n\n<h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/filtering-and-searching/\">Filters</a>  </h3>\n\nDRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.\n\n<h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/graphs-2/\">Graphs</a>  </h3>\n\nAt the bottom left corner of the page, there is a tab that expands to display graphs. Users may toggle between graph styles using the button at the top right of the chart. The data loaded into the graphs is controlled by the currently applied date range and filter set, including geographic filters.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:normal;\">Related Content</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Map Interface', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '28-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 07:42:12', '2017-09-28 07:42:12', '', 28, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/28-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(207, 1, '2017-09-28 07:45:19', '2017-09-28 07:45:19', '\n\nThe map interface is one of the principal tools in the DRIVER application, and is used to view incidents in a variety of ways, such as through filter tools, layers, and more. Depending on the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types\">type of user</a>, the Map also grants access to interventions, additional graphs, custom report builder tools, and data exports, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">How to Access the Map</span>  </h3>\n\nWhile there are small map sections available on the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\">Dashboard</a>, the main Map interface can be accessed by clicking on the the “Dashboard” drop down on the topmost left bar on the DRIVER dashboard.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Important Map Tools</span>  </h3>  <h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/layers/\">Layers</a>  </h3>\n\nLayers allow users to further narrow down the map interface according to Street or Satellite View, or through setting the layer to only show Incidents, Interventions, Heatmap, Blackspots, City/Province, or Region. By setting a layer, users will be able to choose what kind of incident data they want to access. Users can choose more than one layer, or a combination of layers to further narrow down their searches.\n\n<h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/filtering-and-searching/\">Filters</a>  </h3>\n\nDRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.\n\n<h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/graphs-2/\">Graphs</a>  </h3>\n\nAt the bottom left corner of the page, there is a tab that expands to display graphs. Users may toggle between graph styles using the button at the top right of the chart. The data loaded into the graphs is controlled by the currently applied date range and filter set, including geographic filters.\n\nThere are two types of graphs. One is a ToDDoW graph similar to the one on the dashboard. The only difference is that the data is filtered according to what the user sets. The second graph is the total number of incidents over time, aggregated by week. Both graphs provide interactivity on mouse hover.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:normal;\">Related Content</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Map Interface', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '28-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 07:45:19', '2017-09-28 07:45:19', '', 28, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/28-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(208, 1, '2017-09-28 07:48:50', '2017-09-28 07:48:50', '<p style=\"margin-top: -1px;\">DRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.</p>\n\nWhile there are two <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces\">View Interfaces</a> on the DRIVER website (<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a> &amp; <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map Interface</a>), there are also two types of filtering &amp; searching features available:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters.</a>&nbsp;. Attribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website, while Spatial Filters are primarily used for the Map Interface.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Filters</span>  </h1>  <h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as a geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – Attribute Filters and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the Map Interface.\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks. Saved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and spatial filters.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Using Filters with Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  View Interfaces  </li>  <li>  Attribute Filters  </li>  <li>  Spatial Filters  </li>  <li>  Saving &amp; Clearing Filters  </li>  </ul>', 'Filtering & Searching', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 07:48:50', '2017-09-28 07:48:50', '', 89, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(209, 1, '2017-09-28 07:50:49', '2017-09-28 07:50:49', '\n\nDashboard\n\nView Interfaces (Map vs Record List)\n\nFilters\n\nLayers\n\nExporting Data\n\n', 'Getting Started', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '172-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 07:50:49', '2017-09-28 07:50:49', '', 172, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/172-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(213, 1, '2017-09-28 07:52:20', '2017-09-28 07:52:20', '[:en]For analysis outside of the system, data may be exported as a set of CSV files.\r\n<h3>How to Export</h3>\r\nTo export data, go to the Map interface. On the bottom left of the Map, select the \"Export Data\" tab, and click \"Export CSV\". This will automatically export the CSV file into your computer.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-859 size-large\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_3-1024x155.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"835\" height=\"126\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;[:Ph]\r\nData in the map may be exported as a set of CSV files.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\r\n\r\nDRIVER data is stored in a relational database that supports many-to-one relationships. This means that for a given incident, there may be many people and vehicles involved.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\r\n\r\nThe export CSV zip file contains a CSV for each type of related object, linked to the primary accident table via a unique ID.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\r\n\r\nThe CSV files also contain the latitude and longitude for the incident location. These files may be further analyzed using spreadsheet or database software.\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h1>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">View Incidents</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', '[:en]Exporting Data[:]', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'exporting-data', '', '', '2017-12-08 10:14:39', '2017-12-08 10:14:39', '', 0, 'http://roadsafety.ph/?p=213', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(214, 1, '2017-09-28 07:52:20', '2017-09-28 07:52:20', '[:en]Data in the map may be exported as a set of CSV files. DRIVER data is stored in a relational database that supports many-to-one relationships. This means that for a given incident, there may be many people and vehicles involved. The export CSV zip file contains a CSV for each type of related object, linked to the primary accident table via a unique ID. The CSV files also contain the latitude and longitude for the incident location. These files may be further analyzed using spreadsheet or database software.[:]', '[:en]Exporting Data[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '213-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 07:52:20', '2017-09-28 07:52:20', '', 213, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/213-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
