(261, 1, '2017-09-28 11:56:26', '2017-09-28 11:56:26', '\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a> and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/map/\">Map Interface.</a>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Spatial Filters and How to Use Them</span>  </h3>  <h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Region Filter</span>  </h4>\n\nThe Region Filter filters allows the user to select a city, province, or region within the Attribute Filters located at a bar on top of the page.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nOnce the user selects their desired city, province, or region, the Region Filter will automatically zoom in on the map towards the area selected by the user.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\n<h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/custom-area-filter/\">Custom Area Filter</a></span>  </h4>\n\nCustom Area Filters allow users to draw a custom boundary on the Map Interface in order to filter down to incidents that occurred in that area.\n\n<div class=\"pbs-row\" style=\"min-height: 200px;\"><div class=\"pbs-col\" style=\"flex-basis: 50%; justify-content: center;\">\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span><br><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">Rectangular Tool</span>\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"pbs-col\" style=\"flex-basis: 50%; justify-content: center;\">\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">Polygon Tool</span>\n\n</div></div>\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/custom-area-filter/\">Custom Area Filter</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/saving-and-clearing-filters/\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/map/\">Map Interface</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Spatial Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '32-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 11:56:26', '2017-09-28 11:56:26', '', 32, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/32-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(262, 1, '2017-09-28 11:57:16', '2017-09-28 11:57:16', '\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks.\n\nSaved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and spatial filters.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Saving Filters</span>  </h1>\n\nAny chosen set of filters can be saved for later use.\n\nTo save a filter, simply click the “Saved Filters” button on the top right corner of the screen.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\nA pop-up should appear that shows the user’s saved filters (if any). Below, you’ll find a box that says “Add New Saved Filter.”\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nEnter your desired Filter name, and click on “Save Filter.” The new saved filter should now appear inside the pop up.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Clearing Filters</span>  </h1>\n\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button on the top right corner of the screen, next to the Saved Filters button.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  Filtering &amp; Searching  </li>  <li>  Spatial Filters  </li>  <li>  Attribute FiltersView Inerfaces  </li>  <li>  View Interfaces  </li>  </ul>', 'Saving & Clearing Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 11:57:16', '2017-09-28 11:57:16', '', 45, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(263, 1, '2017-09-28 12:00:08', '2017-09-28 12:00:08', '\n\nThe DRIVER application includes functionality to generate custom reports from the database. These reports aggregate counts of incidents according to the rows and columns defined by users generating the reports. The reports also allow for geographic aggregation based on any uploaded boundary layers.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nReports are generated from the map page by clicking Export &gt; Custom Report.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\nThe user is presented with a pop-up window that provides the option to select rows and columns from the data fields defined in the schema.\n\nThe user is also able to specify a geographic aggregation to break the counts of incidents out by the regions of a boundary layer.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Note that any filters that are active for the application will apply to the results of the report.</span>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h1>  <ul>  <li>  Exporting Data  </li>  <li>  User Types &amp; Roles  </li>  </ul>', 'Reporting', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '248-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:00:08', '2017-09-28 12:00:08', '', 248, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/248-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(265, 1, '2017-09-28 12:02:15', '2017-09-28 12:02:15', '\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks.\n\nSaved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/spatial-filters/\">spatial filters.</a>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Saving Filters</span>  </h1>\n\nAny chosen set of filters can be saved for later use.\n\nTo save a filter, simply click the “Saved Filters” button on the top right corner of the screen.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\nA pop-up should appear that shows the user’s saved filters (if any). Below, you’ll find a box that says “Add New Saved Filter.”\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nEnter your desired Filter name, and click on “Save Filter.” The new saved filter should now appear inside the pop up.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Clearing Filters</span>  </h1>\n\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button on the top right corner of the screen, next to the Saved Filters button.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/spatial-filters/\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/view-interfaces/\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Saving & Clearing Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:02:15', '2017-09-28 12:02:15', '', 45, 'http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/28/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(266, 1, '2017-09-28 12:05:03', '2017-09-28 12:05:03', '<p style=\"margin-top: -1px;\">DRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.</p>\n\nWhile there are two <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces\">View Interfaces</a> on the DRIVER website (<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a> &amp; <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map Interface</a>), there are also two types of filtering &amp; searching features available:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters.</a>\n\nAttribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website, while Spatial Filters are primarily used for the Map Interface.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Filters</span>  </h1>  <h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as a geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – Attribute Filters and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the Map Interface.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h1 style=\"margin-top: 20px;\">  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Using Filters with Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/27/view-interfaces/\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/spatial-filters/\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/saving-and-clearing-filters/\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Filtering & Searching', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:05:03', '2017-09-28 12:05:03', '', 89, 'http://roadsafety.ph/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
