(283, 1, '2017-09-28 12:38:42', '2017-09-28 12:38:42', '\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\nThey can be found on the topmost bar of the DRIVER website upon accessing either the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list/\">Record Lis</a>t or <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\">Map Interface</a>.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nThere are two ways to filter incidents on the DRIVER website: through the Record List, or the Map Interface. Unlike the Map Interface, Attribute Filters are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website.\n\n<div class=\"pbs-row\" style=\"min-height: 200px;\"><div class=\"pbs-col\" style=\"flex-basis: 50%; justify-content: center;\">\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map Interface)</span>\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"pbs-col\" style=\"flex-basis: 50%; justify-content: center;\">\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Record List)</span>\n\n</div></div>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h1>  Types of Attribute Filters and How to Access Them  </h1>  <h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Text Search</span>  </h4>\n\nThe Text Search filter can be found in the form of a search field on a bar at the top of both the Record List and the Map Interface.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nSearching in the text box will narrow down the incidents to ones that include the search term in a field marked as filterable/searchable in the database designer.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nTyping multiple words will perform a search for incidents that have both of the words in one or more fields.\n\n<h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Date Filter</span>  </h4>\n\nThe Date Filter can usually be found in between the Text Search Filter and the Option Filter, and narrows down incident data according to a date interval set by the user.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nClicking on the Date Filter launches a clickable interface to choose minimum and maximum dates for display and analysis. The default range of the Date Filter is the previous ninety days.\n\n<h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Option Filter</span>  </h4>\n\nOption filters are shown in the form of enumeration fields (such as select lists and checkboxes), and are included as attribute filter dropdown buttons.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nExamples of option filters include Reporting Agency (concerned in the incident), Main Cause (of the incident), and Severity (of the incident).\n\nSelecting an option applies that filter to the data, and multiple options may be selected for any filter.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nActive filters are highlighted in light blue in the interface.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Numeric Filter</span>  </h4>\n\nFields containing numbers may be filtered using a minimum/maximum range in the numeric filter.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters/\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Attribute Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '40-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:38:42', '2017-09-28 12:38:42', '', 40, 'http://roadsafety.ph/40-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(284, 1, '2017-09-28 12:40:06', '2017-09-28 12:40:06', '\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a> and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\">Map Interface.</a>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Spatial Filters and How to Use Them</span>  </h3>  <h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Region Filter</span>  </h4>\n\nThe Region Filter filters allows the user to select a city, province, or region within the Attribute Filters located at a bar on top of the page.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nOnce the user selects their desired city, province, or region, the Region Filter will automatically zoom in on the map towards the area selected by the user.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\n<h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/custom-area-filter/\">Custom Area Filter</a></span>  </h4>\n\nCustom Area Filters allow users to draw a custom boundary on the Map Interface in order to filter down to incidents that occurred in that area.\n\n<div class=\"pbs-row\" style=\"min-height: 200px;\"><div class=\"pbs-col\" style=\"flex-basis: 50%; justify-content: center;\">\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span><br><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">Rectangular Tool</span>\n\n</div>\n<div class=\"pbs-col\" style=\"flex-basis: 50%; justify-content: center;\">\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">Polygon Tool</span>\n\n</div></div>\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/custom-area-filter/\">Custom Area Filter</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters/\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\">Map Interface</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Spatial Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '32-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:40:06', '2017-09-28 12:40:06', '', 32, 'http://roadsafety.ph/32-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(286, 1, '2017-09-28 12:45:19', '2017-09-28 12:45:19', '<p style=\"margin-top: -1px;\">DRIVER lets users narrow down their searches in order to easily find specific incident entries or sets of incident entries within the DRIVER database.</p>\n\nWhile there are two <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces\">View Interfaces</a> on the DRIVER website (<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">Record List</a> &amp; <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map\">Map Interface</a>), there are also two types of filtering &amp; searching features available:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a>, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters.</a>\n\nAttribute Filters are the different types of filters that are used for both the Record List and the Map Interface of the DRIVER website, while Spatial Filters are primarily used for the Map Interface.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Filters</span>  </h1>  <h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters\">Attribute Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nAttribute Filters help the user narrow down their searches depending on the date of the incident, the reporting agency responsible, and the severity of the incident, among others.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters\">Spatial Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as a geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – Attribute Filters and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the Map Interface.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a></span>  </h3>\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h1 style=\"margin-top: 20px;\">  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Using Filters with Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces/\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters/\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Filtering & Searching', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '89-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:45:19', '2017-09-28 12:45:19', '', 89, 'http://roadsafety.ph/89-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(287, 1, '2017-09-28 12:47:12', '2017-09-28 12:47:12', '\n\nApplied filter sets can be saved for later use. The saved filters interface allows users to save and name the currently applied filters, and lists previously saved filters. This can be useful for defining a combination of filters used to create reports, exports, or other analysis tasks.\n\nSaved filters do not apply to geographic boundary selections or date ranges, but act on search, option, and <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\">spatial filters.</a>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Saving Filters</span>  </h1>\n\nAny chosen set of filters can be saved for later use.\n\nTo save a filter, simply click the “Saved Filters” button on the top right corner of the screen.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\nA pop-up should appear that shows the user’s saved filters (if any). Below, you’ll find a box that says “Add New Saved Filter.”\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nEnter your desired Filter name, and click on “Save Filter.” The new saved filter should now appear inside the pop up.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">GIF HERE</span>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Clearing Filters</span>  </h1>\n\nFilters may be reset to default state by clicking the clear filter button on the top right corner of the screen, next to the Saved Filters button.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/spatial-filters/\">Spatial Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/view-interfaces/\">View Interfaces</a>  </li>  </ul>', 'Saving & Clearing Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:47:12', '2017-09-28 12:47:12', '', 45, 'http://roadsafety.ph/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(288, 1, '2017-10-02 05:17:49', '2017-10-02 05:17:49', '\n\nDRIVER is website designed to view, collect, and analyze data about road incidents that occur at a particular place in the Philippines. These include traffic incidents and crimes. The application provides data viewing and entry tools, graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.\n\n<p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\">Depending on the type of user,&nbsp;</p> <h3> Related Articles </h3> <ul> <li> <a href=\"http://accessing-driver\">Accessing Driver</a> </li> <li> <a href=\"http://user-types-and-permissions\">User Types &amp; Permissions</a> </li> <li> <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-tools\">Important Tools on DRIVER</a> </li> <li> <a href=\"http://http\">Explore the Dashboard</a> </li> </ul>', '[:en]About DRIVER[:Ph]Tungkol sa DRIVER[:tl]Getting Started[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '172-autosave-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 05:20:38', '2017-10-02 05:20:38', '', 172, 'http://roadsafety.ph/172-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(289, 1, '2017-09-28 12:55:45', '2017-09-28 12:55:45', '\n\nDRIVER is designed to collect and analyze data about incidents that occur at a particular place, such as traffic accidents or crimes. The application provides data entry tools, graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.\n\nSigning In\n\nView Interfaces\n\nFilters\n\nView Interfaces (Map vs Record List)\n\nFilters\n\nLayers\n\nExporting Data\n\n', '[:en]About DRIVER[:tl]Getting Started[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '172-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:55:45', '2017-09-28 12:55:45', '', 172, 'http://roadsafety.ph/172-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(290, 1, '2017-09-28 12:56:23', '2017-09-28 12:56:23', '<div data-ce-tag=\"spacer\"></div>\r\n<h1>  <b>Getting Started</b>  </h1>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">DRIVER is designed to collect and analyze data about incidents that occur at a particular place, such as traffic accidents or crimes. The application provides data entry tools, graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  <b>Related Articles</b>  </h3>  <ul>  <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">  <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Signing In</span>  </li>  <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">  <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">User Roles/Types of Users</span>  </li>  <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">  <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dashboard</span>  </li>  <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">  <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Maps</span>  </li>  <li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">  <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Entering Data</span>  </li>  </ul>', '[:en]About DRIVER[:tl]Getting Started[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 12:56:23', '2017-09-28 12:56:23', '', 16, 'http://roadsafety.ph/16-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(293, 1, '2017-09-28 13:01:19', '2017-09-28 13:01:19', '\n\nEconomic loss and societal harm costs are calculated based on an Ashlar configuration. Administrators choose an option-type field associated with the primary record type, such as “Severity”, and associate a cost with each of its values.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nIn the DRIVER interface, this cost is displayed both in the dashboard and map views. The cost totals respect the geographic, temporal, and attribute filters applied in the map. This makes it possible for a user to associate an estimated cost for a search like <span style=\"font-style:italic;\">crashes involving pedestrians in a certain neighborhood in 2016.</span>\n\n', '[:en]Cost to Society[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '281-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 13:01:19', '2017-09-28 13:01:19', '', 281, 'http://roadsafety.ph/281-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(294, 1, '2017-09-28 13:05:34', '2017-09-28 13:05:34', '\n\nEnforcer reports are designed for optimizing the deployment of traffic enforcers by focusing on the roads predicted to have the highest likelihood of traffic incidents. The reports take statistical predictions using location, time of day, day of week, and day of year, and then output a set number of locations.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\nThe reports are designed for printing and distribution at the beginning of a shift. An area for notes allows enforcer captains to include additional details for the shift and location.\n\n', '[:en]Enforcer Reports[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '279-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 13:05:34', '2017-09-28 13:05:34', '', 279, 'http://roadsafety.ph/279-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(295, 1, '2017-09-28 13:12:12', '2017-09-28 13:12:12', '\n\nBlack spots are sections of roadway or intersections that experience an unusually high number of traffic crashes. Black spot locations are calculated on a daily basis with a server-side R script. The script uses a gradient boosted model (GBM) to predict severe and non-severe crashes in traffic segments based on geography and historical severe and non-severe crashes. Black spots require a minimum of one year of consistent data to produce the best results.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Modeling</span>  </h1>\n\nThis section explains inputs and outputs of the black spots model. The black spots model ingests the data below and predicts crashes in road segments. The purpose of the GBM is to learn from all of the available information. One possible alternative to this type of model is a simple historical average, for example, expecting that this year, each segment will have as many crashes as it did last year. The “counting model” doesn’t have any understanding of a “surprisingly” high count, and would be very wrong any time unusually high counts or unusually low counts in a segment didn’t carry over from one year to the next.\n\nThe GBM predicts based on more than historical counts and predicts for groups of segments that are similar to each other instead of individual segments. There are three benefits to using the GBM instead of other classes of model. First, a GBM will more effectively handle regression to the mean than counting models will. Other models, for example, linear regression models, also better handle regression to the mean than counting models, but, second, GBMs more gracefully handle non-linearity and interaction effects than linear models. Finally, because GBMs have several tunable hyperparameters, the black spots prediction script can search over the possible GBMs to pick the best one.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Input Variables</span>  </h1>\n\nEach of the variables in the following list must be included in an input CSV for the model to be able to run. Below, a “segment” refers to a section of road or an intersection and “present” refers to the final year of training data.\n\n• inter: (binary) whether a segment contains an intersection\n\n• length: (float) the length of a segment in the units of the projection\n\n• lines: (integer) the number of line segments comprising the traffic segment in which the crash\n\noccurred. All segments with more than one line contain an intersection.\n\n• pointx: (float) the x coordinate of the centroid of the segment, in the units of the projection\n\n• pointy: (float) the y coordinate of the centroid of the segment, in the units of the projection\n\n• t0notsev: (integer) the number of non-severe crashes in the segment in t0, where t0 is the\n\ncurrent period, extending from a year ago to the present\n\n• t0sev: (integer) the number of severe crashes in the segment in t0\n\n• tXXnotsev: (integer) the number of non-severe crashes in the segment in tXX, where tXX is the\n\nperiod spanning from XX years before the present to one year before that. For example, t1\n\nincludes from two years before the present to one year before the present.\n\n• tXXsev: (integer) the number of severe crashes in the segment in tXX\n\nFor tXXnotsev and tXXsev, the script will by default look for variables matching from t3 to t1 for training and will look for a t0 or t1 for results. This behavior can be modified in the PrepData function.\n\nA preprocessing script creates these values from OpenStreetMap data and road safety records. The preprocessing step performs three functions to transform crash records and road shapefiles into the data used above.\n\nFirst, the preprocessing script identifies all intersections and assigns a buffer zone around each intersection to that intersection. In cases where buffer zones from intersections overlap, those intersections can be assigned to the same segment.\n\nSecond, it breaks all stretches of road without intersections into smaller pieces. This step is necessary because identifying, for example, a 10-mile stretch of road as a black spot doesn’t provide good information about where along that stretch is dangerous or whether the stretch of road has more\n\ncrashes because it’s a long stretch of road.\n\nFinally, it assigns every crash record to its nearest road segment and aggregates crash counts by\n\nsegment and time period.\n\n', '[:en]Blackspot Identification[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '275-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 13:12:12', '2017-09-28 13:12:12', '', 275, 'http://roadsafety.ph/275-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(296, 1, '2017-09-28 14:08:43', '2017-09-28 14:08:43', '\n\nData in the map may be exported as a set of CSV files.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\n\nDRIVER data is stored in a relational database that supports many-to-one relationships. This means that for a given incident, there may be many people and vehicles involved.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\n\nThe export CSV zip file contains a CSV for each type of related object, linked to the primary accident table via a unique ID.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\n\nThe CSV files also contain the latitude and longitude for the incident location. These files may be further analyzed using spreadsheet or database software.\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h1>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">View Incidents</a>  </li>  </ul>', '[:en]Exporting Data[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '213-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 14:08:43', '2017-09-28 14:08:43', '', 213, 'http://roadsafety.ph/213-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(297, 1, '2017-09-28 14:59:23', '2017-09-28 14:59:23', '<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Native Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  Street View  </h3>\n\nThe Street View option shows the user a simple roadmap view.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h3>  Satelite View  </h3>\n\nThe Satellite View option shows a more detailed, satellite view of the map, with data from OpenStreetMap.com. Users can switch between both views.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE</span>\n\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Geographic Boundary Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  Incidents  </h3>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Button)</span>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Map)</span>\n\n<h3>  Interventions  </h3>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\n\n<h3>  Heatmap  </h3>\n\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\n\n<h3>  Blackspots  </h3>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\n\n<h3>  City/Province  </h3>\n\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)<br>SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\n\n<h3>  Region  </h3>\n\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)<br>SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\n\n', '[:en]Layers[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '193-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-09-28 14:59:23', '2017-09-28 14:59:23', '', 193, 'http://roadsafety.ph/193-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(298, 1, '2017-09-29 06:32:04', '2017-09-29 06:32:04', '[:en]Analyst users have additional access to certain parts of DRIVER, and can both view and input data, as well as edit and delete already existing data.\r\n<h3>Add, Edit, and Delete Data</h3>\r\nAn analyst user\'s interface on the DRIVER website gets additional analyst-exclusive features, such as buttons to add, edit, and delete incident and intervention reports.\r\n<h3>Access to Additional Data and Filters</h3>\r\nAdditional data is also accessible by the Analyst user. Examples include access to vehicle information, persons involved in the incident, and photos of the incidents. Aside from this, Analysts also have an additional filter to narrow down searches according to vehicle type.\r\n<h3>Export Data as CSV files</h3>\r\nAnalysts also have the ability to export data as CSV files, which can be downloaded and converted into spreadsheets for further data analysis.\r\n<h3>Manage Duplicate Records</h3>\r\nOccasionally, two users may input the same incident. DRIVER has a process that runs on record creation and nightly to identify potential duplicate incidents. Admin and Analyst users may access an interface to identify and resolve the duplicates.\r\n<h3>Assign Traffic Enforcers to a Selected Area</h3>\r\nAnalysts also have the ability to assign traffic enforcers to selected areas via the DRIVER website.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;[:Ph]\r\nAnalyst users have additional access to certain parts of DRIVER, and can both view and input data, as well as edit data already existing data.\r\n\r\nManaging Duplicate Records\r\n\r\n[:]', '[:en]Analyst User Overview[:]', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'analyst', '', '', '2017-10-04 06:07:19', '2017-10-04 06:07:19', '', 0, 'http://roadsafety.ph/?p=298', 0, 'post', '', 0),
