(555, 1, '2017-10-02 07:28:25', '2017-10-02 07:28:25', '[:en]Unlike Filters, setting a layer lets users choose what kind of incident data they want to access: <strong>Incidents, Interventions, Heatmap, Blackspots, City/Province, or Region</strong>. Users may also choose between viewing the Street View or the Satellite View. Users can choose more than one layer, or a combination of layers to further narrow down their searches.\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety,ph/native-layers\" xlink=\"href\">Native Layers</a></h3>\r\n<h4>Street View</h4>\r\nThe Street View option shows the user a simple roadmap view of the Philippines, which is the default map view on the DRIVER Dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-336 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Map.png\" width=\"1365\" height=\"588\" />\r\n<h3>Satelite View</h3>\r\nThe Satellite View option shows a pictured and more detailed view of the map, with data from OpenStreetMap.com. Users can switch between both the Satellite View and Street View by selecting the “Layers” option on the upper right corner of the map.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-338 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Satellite.png\" width=\"1365\" height=\"535\" />\r\n<h1><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Geographic Boundary Layers</span></h1>\r\n<h1>Incidents</h1>\r\nThese are the incidents recorded into the DRIVER Website by Analyst users. Incident data includes:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>The date and time of the incident’s occurrence</li>\r\n 	<li>The location of the incident</li>\r\n 	<li>The time and date of when the incident was added to the DRIVER database</li>\r\n 	<li>Longitude &amp; Latitude</li>\r\n 	<li>Weather during the incident</li>\r\n 	<li>Light (if the incident occurred during the evening or the morning)</li>\r\n 	<li>Severity</li>\r\n 	<li>Collission Type</li>\r\n 	<li>Reporting Agency</li>\r\n 	<li>Location Approximate, and</li>\r\n 	<li>Additional details of the incident</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Button)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Interventions</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">(TO FOLLOW c/o MIRICK)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Heatmap</h3>\r\nThe heatmap represents the volume of the severity of incidents in a particular area.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Blackspots</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n<h3>City/Province</h3>\r\nThe City/Province layer shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\r\n<h3>Region</h3>\r\nAs with the City/Province layer, the Region layer also shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Map)[:Ph]\r\nUnlike Filters, setting a layer lets users choose what kind of incident data they want to access: Incidents, Interventions, Heatmap, Blackspots, City/Province, or Region. Users may also choose between viewing the Street View or the Satelite View. Users can choose more than one layer, or a combination of layers to further narrow down their searches.\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Native Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  Street View  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe Street View option shows the user a simple roadmap view of the Philippines, which is the default map view on the DRIVER Dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-336 size-full\" height=\"588\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Map.png\" width=\"1365\">\r\n\r\n<h3>  Satelite View  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe Satellite View option shows a pictured and more detailed view of the map, with data from OpenStreetMap.com. Users can switch between both the Satellite View and Street View by selecting the “Layers” option on the upper right corner of the map.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-338 size-full\" height=\"535\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Satellite.png\" width=\"1365\">\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Geographic Boundary Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  Incidents  </h3>\r\n\r\nThese are the incidents recorded into the DRIVER Website by Analyst users. Incident data includes:\r\n\r\n<ul>  <li>  The date and time of the incident’s occurrence  </li>  <li>  The location of the incident  </li>  <li>  The time and date of when the incident was added to the DRIVER database  </li>  <li>  Longitude &amp; Latitude  </li>  <li>  Weather during the incident  </li>  <li>  Light (if the incident occurred during the evening or the morning)  </li>  <li>  Severity  </li>  <li>  Collission Type  </li>  <li>  Reporting Agency  </li>  <li>  Location Approximate, and  </li>  <li>  Additional details of the incident  </li>  </ul>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Button)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  Interventions  </h3>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">(TO FOLLOW)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  Heatmap  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe heatmap represents the volume of the severity of incidents in a particular area.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  Blackspots  </h3>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  City/Province  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe City/Province layer shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)<br>SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\r\n\r\n<h3>  Region  </h3>\r\n\r\nAs with the City/Province layer, the Region layer also shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)<br>SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\r\n\r\n[:]', '[:en]Layers[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '193-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 07:28:25', '2017-10-02 07:28:25', '', 193, 'http://roadsafety.ph/193-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(564, 1, '2017-10-02 07:38:16', '2017-10-02 07:38:16', '[:en]Graphs are available on the Map Interface by selecting the bottom left corner of the page, where a tab can be found that expands to display graphs.\r\n\r\nUsers may toggle between graph styles using the button at the top right of the chart. The data loaded into the graphs is controlled by the currently applied date range and filter set, including geographic filters.\r\n\r\nThere are two types of graphs. One is a ToDDoW graph similar to the one on the dashboard. The only difference is that the data is filtered according to what the user sets.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Highlight_Graphs_1.png\" />\r\n<div class=\"pbs-row\">\r\n<div class=\"pbs-col\">\r\n\r\nThe second graph is the total number of incidents over time, aggregated by week. Both graphs provide interactivity on mouse hover.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-353 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Hghlight_Graph_2.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" srcset=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Hghlight_Graph_2.png 600w, http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Hghlight_Graph_2-300x148.png 300w\" width=\"600\" height=\"295\" />[:]', '[:en]Graphs[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '553-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 07:38:16', '2017-10-02 07:38:16', '', 553, 'http://roadsafety.ph/553-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(565, 1, '2017-10-02 07:41:16', '2017-10-02 07:41:16', '[:en]DRIVER is website designed to view, collect, and analyze data about road incidents that occur at a particular place in the Philippines. These include traffic incidents and crimes. The application provides data viewing and entry tools, graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-roles-and-permissions\" xlink=\"href\">User Types &amp; Permissions</a></h3>\r\n<p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\">There are different <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-roles\" xlink=\"href\">types of users</a> on the DRIVER website, each with a designated role. <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/public-viewer\" xlink=\"href\">Public Viewers</a> may view data on DRIVER, but with limitations (i.e. they may not access plate numbers, names of persons involved in the accident, etc). <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/analyst\" xlink=\"href\">Analysts</a> may enter, edit, and export data. <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/administrator\" xlink=\"href\">Administrators</a> have login capabilities to the database and design editor of the software, and can modify the structure of the database.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/accessing-driver\" xlink=\"href\">Accessing DRIVER</a></h3>\r\nTo access DRIVER, go to <a href=\"http://roadsafety.gov.ph.\" xlink=\"href\">http://roadsafety.gov.ph.</a> If a user has an account with a supported provider (e.g. Google), they can click on the “Log in with provider’” button.\r\n<h3>Related Articles</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/accessing-driver\" xlink=\"href\">Accessing Driver</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://user-types-and-permissions\" xlink=\"href\">User Types &amp; Permissions</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-tools\" xlink=\"href\">Important Tools on DRIVER</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\" xlink=\"href\">Explore the Dashboard</a></li>\r\n</ul>[:Ph]\r\nDRIVER is website designed to view, collect, and analyze data about road incidents that occur at a particular place in the Philippines. These include traffic incidents and crimes. The application provides data viewing and entry tools, graph and map interfaces, custom report and filter tools, multiple concurrent user editing, and data exports.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-roles-and-permissions\">User Types &amp; Permissions</a>  </h3>  <p style=\"margin-top: -2px;\">There are different <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-and-permissions\">types of users</a> on the DRIVER website, each with a designated role. <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/public-viewer\">Public Viewers</a> may view data on DRIVER, but with limitations (i.e. they may not access plate numbers, names of persons involved in the accident, etc). <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/analyst\">Analysts</a>&nbsp;may enter, edit, and export data. <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/administrator\">Administrators</a>&nbsp;have login capabilities to the database and design editor of the software, and can modify the structure of the database.</p>  <h3>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/accessing-driver\">Accessing DRIVER</a>  </h3>\r\n\r\nTo access DRIVER, go to <a href=\"http://roadsafety.gov.ph.\">http://roadsafety.gov.ph.</a>&nbsp;If a user has an account with a supported provider (e.g. Google), they can click on the “Log in with provider’” button.\r\n\r\n<h3>  Related Articles  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/accessing-driver\">Accessing Driver</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://user-types-and-permissions\">User Types &amp; Permissions</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-tools\">Important Tools on DRIVER</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/dashboard\">Explore the Dashboard</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', '[:en]About DRIVER[:Ph]Tungkol sa DRIVER[:tl]Getting Started[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '172-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 07:41:16', '2017-10-02 07:41:16', '', 172, 'http://roadsafety.ph/172-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(567, 1, '2017-10-02 07:43:53', '2017-10-02 07:43:53', '[:en]<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-admin\" xlink=\"href\">Admin</a></h3>\r\nThe admin role has access to the most functionality in the application, including login capability to the database design editor software. Admins can modify the structure of the database, add new fields, make fields required, upload geographic boundaries, and manage users. The database design editor software will be covered in a separate user manual. In DRIVER, admins may export user access logs for analysis.\r\n<h3>Related Articles</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/user-types-and-roles\" xlink=\"href\">User Types &amp; Roles</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/analyst\" xlink=\"href\">Analyst</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/public-viewer\" xlink=\"href\">Public Viewer</a></li>\r\n</ul>[:]', '[:en]Admin[:]', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'administrator', '', '', '2017-10-02 18:52:06', '2017-10-02 18:52:06', '', 0, 'http://roadsafety.ph/?p=567', 0, 'post', '', 0),
