(574, 1, '2017-10-02 08:01:55', '2017-10-02 08:01:55', '[:en]Spatial Filters are tools that act as geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\" xlink=\"href\">Attribute Filters</a> and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\" xlink=\"href\">Map Interface.</a>\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/region-filter\" xlink=\"href\">Region Filter</a></h3>\r\nThe Region Filter filters allows the user to select a city, province, or region within the Attribute Filters located at a bar on top of the page. Users may select a Region Filter either on the Map Interface or the Dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-361 size-full\" style=\"width: 100%; height: auto;\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Province-Default.png\" width=\"798\" height=\"439\" />Once the user selects their desired city, province, or region, the Region Filter will automatically zoom in on the map towards the area selected by the user.\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/custom-area-filter/\" xlink=\"href\">Custom Area Filter</a></h3>\r\nCustom Area Filters allow users to draw a custom boundary on the Map Interface in order to filter down to incidents that occurred in that area.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-388 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/03_Content-Area-Tools_01-Rectangular-Tool_05-Pop-up.gif\" width=\"800\" height=\"444\" />\r\n<h3>Related Articles</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/custom-area-filter/\" xlink=\"href\">Custom Area Filter</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\" xlink=\"href\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters/\" xlink=\"href\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\" xlink=\"href\">Map Interface</a></li>\r\n</ul>[:Ph]\r\nSpatial Filters are tools that act as geographic boundary filters. While there are two types of filters on the DRIVER website – <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/attribute-filters/\">Attribute Filters</a> and Spatial Filters – Spatial Filters are used primarily for the <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\">Map Interface.</a>\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Types of Spatial Filters and How to Use Them</span>  </h3>  <h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Region Filter</span>  </h4>\r\n\r\nThe Region Filter filters allows the user to select a city, province, or region within the Attribute Filters located at a bar on top of the page. Users may select a Region Filter either on the Map Interface or the Dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-361 size-full\" height=\"439\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Province-Default.png\" style=\"width: 100%; height: auto;\" width=\"798\">Once the user selects their desired city, province, or region, the Region Filter will automatically zoom in on the map towards the area selected by the user.\r\n\r\n<h4>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/custom-area-filter/\">Custom Area Filter</a></span>  </h4>\r\n\r\nCustom Area Filters allow users to draw a custom boundary on the Map Interface in order to filter down to incidents that occurred in that area.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-388 size-full\" height=\"444\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/03_Content-Area-Tools_01-Rectangular-Tool_05-Pop-up.gif\" width=\"800\">\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/custom-area-filter/\">Custom Area Filter</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/filtering-and-searching/\">Filtering &amp; Searching</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/saving-and-clearing-filters/\">Saving &amp; Clearing Filters</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/map/\">Map Interface</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', 'Spatial Filters', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '32-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 08:01:55', '2017-10-02 08:01:55', '', 32, 'http://roadsafety.ph/32-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(575, 1, '2017-10-02 08:02:59', '2017-10-02 08:02:59', '[:en]<img class=\"wp-image-362 size-full aligncenter\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Region-Default.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" srcset=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Region-Default.png 800w, http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Region-Default-300x165.png 300w, http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Region-Default-768x423.png 768w\" width=\"800\" height=\"441\" /><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-361 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Province-Default.png\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" srcset=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Province-Default.png 800w, http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Province-Default-300x165.png 300w, http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Province-Default-768x423.png 768w\" width=\"800\" height=\"441\" />\r\n\r\nA header bar on the Dashboard allows users to set a default city, province, or region, which when selected, the Dashboard’s Application Defaults will automatically adjust to. The region chosen will filter the maps, ToDDoW chart, and widgets to provide data for incidents that occurred only within that geographic boundary.\r\n\r\nThis default setting is preserved between user sessions on the same computer.[:]', '[:en]Region Default[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '531-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 08:02:59', '2017-10-02 08:02:59', '', 531, 'http://roadsafety.ph/531-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(577, 1, '2017-10-02 08:12:17', '2017-10-02 08:12:17', '[:en]Unlike Filters, setting a layer lets users choose what kind of incident data they want to access: <strong>Incidents, Interventions, Heatmap, Blackspots, City/Province, or Region</strong>. Users may also choose between viewing the Street View or the Satellite View. Users can choose more than one layer, or a combination of layers to further narrow down their searches.\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety,ph/native-layers\" xlink=\"href\">Native Layers</a></h3>\r\n<h4>Street View</h4>\r\nThe Street View option shows the user a simple roadmap view of the Philippines, which is the default map view on the DRIVER Dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-336 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Map.png\" width=\"1365\" height=\"588\" />\r\n<h3>Satelite View</h3>\r\nThe Satellite View option shows a pictured and more detailed view of the map, with data from OpenStreetMap.com. Users can switch between both the Satellite View and Street View by selecting the “Layers” option on the upper right corner of the map.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-338 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Satellite.png\" width=\"1365\" height=\"535\" />\r\n<h3><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/geographic-boundary-layers\" xlink=\"href\">Geographic Boundary Layers</a></h3>\r\n<h4>Incidents</h4>\r\nThese are the incidents recorded into the DRIVER Website by Analyst users. Examples of Incident Data include (but are not limited to):\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>The date and time of the incident’s occurrence</li>\r\n 	<li>When the incident was added to the DRIVER database</li>\r\n 	<li>The location of the incident</li>\r\n 	<li>Longitude &amp; Latitude</li>\r\n 	<li>Weather during the incident</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Button)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Interventions</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">(TO FOLLOW c/o MIRICK)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Heatmap</h3>\r\nThe heatmap represents the volume of the severity of incidents in a particular area.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; font-weight: bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Blackspots</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold; text-decoration: underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n<h3>Region &amp; City/Province</h3>\r\nThe City/Province layer shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other. As with the City/Province layer, the Region layer also does the same.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\r\n<h3>Related Articles</h3>\r\n&nbsp;[:Ph]\r\nUnlike Filters, setting a layer lets users choose what kind of incident data they want to access: Incidents, Interventions, Heatmap, Blackspots, City/Province, or Region. Users may also choose between viewing the Street View or the Satelite View. Users can choose more than one layer, or a combination of layers to further narrow down their searches.\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Native Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  Street View  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe Street View option shows the user a simple roadmap view of the Philippines, which is the default map view on the DRIVER Dashboard.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-336 size-full\" height=\"588\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Map.png\" width=\"1365\">\r\n\r\n<h3>  Satelite View  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe Satellite View option shows a pictured and more detailed view of the map, with data from OpenStreetMap.com. Users can switch between both the Satellite View and Street View by selecting the “Layers” option on the upper right corner of the map.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-338 size-full\" height=\"535\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_Zoom_Satellite.png\" width=\"1365\">\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Geographic Boundary Layers</span>  </h1>  <h3>  Incidents  </h3>\r\n\r\nThese are the incidents recorded into the DRIVER Website by Analyst users. Incident data includes:\r\n\r\n<ul>  <li>  The date and time of the incident’s occurrence  </li>  <li>  The location of the incident  </li>  <li>  The time and date of when the incident was added to the DRIVER database  </li>  <li>  Longitude &amp; Latitude  </li>  <li>  Weather during the incident  </li>  <li>  Light (if the incident occurred during the evening or the morning)  </li>  <li>  Severity  </li>  <li>  Collission Type  </li>  <li>  Reporting Agency  </li>  <li>  Location Approximate, and  </li>  <li>  Additional details of the incident  </li>  </ul>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Button)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Incident Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  Interventions  </h3>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">(TO FOLLOW)</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  Heatmap  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe heatmap represents the volume of the severity of incidents in a particular area.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"text-decoration:underline;font-weight:bold;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  Blackspots  </h3>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Button)</span><br><span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)</span>\r\n\r\n<h3>  City/Province  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe City/Province layer shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)<br>SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\r\n\r\n<h3>  Region  </h3>\r\n\r\nAs with the City/Province layer, the Region layer also shows a visual boundary that segregates provinces from each other.\r\n\r\nSCREENSHOT HERE (Button)<br>SCREENSHOT HERE (Map)\r\n\r\n[:]', '[:en]Layers[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '193-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 08:12:17', '2017-10-02 08:12:17', '', 193, 'http://roadsafety.ph/193-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(578, 1, '2017-10-02 08:12:29', '2017-10-02 08:12:29', '[:en]There are three roles with differing permissions in DRIVER: the (1) Admin, (2) Analyst, and (3) Public Viewer. Each “user type” or role provides different levels of functionality, and some have limited access to certain parts of DRIVER.\r\n<h3 style=\"margin-top: 20px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-admin\" xlink=\"href\">Admin</a></span></h3>\r\nThe admin role has access to the most functionality in the application, including login capability to the database design editor software. Admins can modify the structure of the database, add new fields, make fields required, upload geographic boundaries, and manage users. The database design editor software will be covered in a separate user manual. In DRIVER, admins may export user access logs for analysis.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"http://driver-analyst\" xlink=\"href\">Analyst</a></span></h3>\r\nThe analyst role includes permissions to view and edit all data in DRIVER. Analysts may add, edit, and delete incidents and interventions, and have access to all event information, including details associated with an incident such as people and vehicle information.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-public-viewer\" xlink=\"href\">Public Viewer</a></span></h3>\r\nPublic users may register to view basic incident data. They may not edit any data, and can not view person or vehicle information.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Related Articles</span></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/getting-started/\" xlink=\"href\">Getting Started</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-admin\" xlink=\"href\">Admin</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-analyst\" xlink=\"href\">Analyst</a></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-public-viewer\" xlink=\"href\">Public Viewer</a></li>\r\n</ul>[:Ph]There are three roles with differing permissions in DRIVER: the (1) Admin, (2) Analyst, and (3) Public Viewer. Each “user type” or role provides different levels of functionality, and some have limited access to certain parts of DRIVER.\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"margin-top: 20px;\">  <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-admin\">Admin</a></span>  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe admin role has access to the most functionality in the application, including login capability to the database design editor software. Admins can modify the structure of the database, add new fields, make fields required, upload geographic boundaries, and manage users. The database design editor software will be covered in a separate user manual. In DRIVER, admins may export user access logs for analysis.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"http://driver-analyst\">Analyst</a></span>  </h3>\r\n\r\nThe analyst role includes permissions to view and edit all data in DRIVER. Analysts may add, edit, and delete incidents and interventions, and have access to all event information, including details associated with an incident such as people and vehicle information.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"><a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-public-viewer\">Public Viewer</a></span>  </h3>\r\n\r\nPublic users may register to view basic incident data. They may not edit any data, and can not view person or vehicle information.\r\n\r\n<h3>  <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h3>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/2017/09/26/getting-started/\" xlink=\"href\">Getting Started</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-admin\">Admin</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-analyst\">Analyst</a>  </li>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/driver-public-viewer\">Public Viewer</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', 'User Types & Roles', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '95-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-02 08:12:29', '2017-10-02 08:12:29', '', 95, 'http://roadsafety.ph/95-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
