(860, 1, '2017-10-03 16:32:10', '2017-10-03 16:32:10', '[:en]For analysis outside of the system, data may be exported as a set of CSV files.\r\n\r\n<strong>How to Export</strong>\r\n\r\nTo export data, go to the Map interface. On the bottom left of the Map, select the \"Export Data\" tab, and click \"Export CSV\".\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone wp-image-859 size-large\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Screenshot_3-1024x155.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"835\" height=\"126\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;[:Ph]\r\nData in the map may be exported as a set of CSV files.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\r\n\r\nDRIVER data is stored in a relational database that supports many-to-one relationships. This means that for a given incident, there may be many people and vehicles involved.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\r\n\r\nThe export CSV zip file contains a CSV for each type of related object, linked to the primary accident table via a unique ID.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight:bold;text-decoration:underline;\">SCREENSHOTS</span>\r\n\r\nThe CSV files also contain the latitude and longitude for the incident location. These files may be further analyzed using spreadsheet or database software.\r\n\r\n<h1>  <span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Related Articles</span>  </h1>  <ul>  <li>  <a href=\"http://roadsafety.ph/record-list\">View Incidents</a>  </li>  </ul>[:]', '[:en]Exporting Data[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '213-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-03 16:32:10', '2017-10-03 16:32:10', '', 213, 'http://roadsafety.ph/213-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(861, 1, '2017-10-03 16:33:48', '2017-10-03 16:33:48', '[:en]<h3>Viewing Incidents by Road Vulnerability</h3>\r\n<img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-633 size-full\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Layers_Blackspots.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1365\" height=\"634\" />\r\n\r\nBlack spots are sections of roadway or intersections that experience an unusually high number of traffic\r\ncrashes.\r\n\r\nTo view the black spots of a particular area, go to the Map interface of the page, select the layers button, and tick \"Black Spots.\"\r\n<h3>Viewing Incidents by Severity</h3>\r\n<h3><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-632 size-full\" style=\"font-size: 14px;\" src=\"http://roadsafety.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/Layers_Heatmap.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1364\" height=\"636\" /></h3>\r\nThe heatmap represents the volume of the severity of incidents in a particular area.\r\n\r\nTo use the heatmap go to the Map, select the layers button, and tick \"Heat map\".\r\n\r\nThe heat map and black spots may also be used together with other filters on the DRIVER website.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;[:]', '[:en]Road Vulnerability[:]', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '827-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-10-03 16:33:48', '2017-10-03 16:33:48', '', 827, 'http://roadsafety.ph/827-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
